<subSubSection pageId="9" pageNumber="160" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="9.[151,1436,1445,1758]" pageId="9" pageNumber="160">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,504,1589,1614]" pageId="9" pageNumber="160">Distribution and habitat.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName box="[514,697,1589,1614]" class="Reptilia" family="Gymnophthalmidae" genus="Bachia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="9" pageNumber="160" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="peruana">
<emphasis box="[514,697,1589,1614]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="160">Bachia peruana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is endemic to southwestern 
<taxonomicName box="[1034,1152,1589,1614]" class="Sordariomycetes" family="Meliolaceae" genus="Amazonia" kingdom="Fungi" order="Meliolales" pageId="9" pageNumber="195" phylum="Ascomycota" rank="genus">Amazonia</taxonomicName>
, occurring in 
<collectingCountry box="[1317,1385,1589,1614]" name="Brazil" pageId="9" pageNumber="160">Brazil</collectingCountry>
and 
<collectingCountry box="[151,203,1626,1649]" name="Peru" pageId="9" pageNumber="160">Peru</collectingCountry>
(
<figureCitation box="[224,297,1625,1650]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="5.[151,250,1113,1135]" captionTargetBox="[154,1434,189,1086]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[151,1436,179,1091]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 3. Distribution of examined material of Amapasaurus tetradactylus, B. panoplia, B. peruana, B. pyburni, B. remota, B. scolecoides, and B. trisanale. Records of Bachia didactyla and B. scaea were obtained from the literature." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/581978/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="160">Fig. 3</figureCitation>
). In 
<collectingCountry box="[362,433,1625,1650]" name="Brazil" pageId="9" pageNumber="160">Brazil</collectingCountry>
, it is known from the states of 
<collectingRegion box="[828,946,1626,1650]" country="Peru" name="Amazonas" pageId="9" pageNumber="160">Amazonas</collectingRegion>
and 
<collectingRegion box="[1013,1070,1626,1650]" country="Brazil" name="Acre" pageId="9" pageNumber="160">Acre</collectingRegion>
, restricted to the Juruá–Envira interfluvium. 
<taxonomicName box="[309,495,1661,1686]" class="Reptilia" family="Gymnophthalmidae" genus="Bachia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="9" pageNumber="160" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="peruana">
<emphasis box="[309,495,1661,1686]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="160">Bachia peruana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is fossorial and diurnal (Schlüter 
<emphasis box="[902,963,1661,1686]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="160">et al.</emphasis>
2004), inhabits primary terra firme and flooded forests (Pantoja &amp; Fraga 2012). Dixon (1973) reported the species “under rotting logs and in loose soil beneath decaying vegetation in coffee groves”.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
